ce:section.ce:para:
Temporally-shaped femtosecond laser (Fig. S2): Femtosecond laser (Q800 nm, 35 fs, 1 kHz, pulse interval (
τ 1
) is 1 ms, Specta Physics, Inc) pulses are shaped into two subpulses (1:1 energy ratio) after passing through the beam splitter and combined at the mirror (M4). The horizontal position of the mirror (M3) is used to realize the reflection of a sub-pulse and control the optical path difference of the two sub-pulses after splitting. So that we can realize the control of the laser pulse delay. Since the speed of light is about 3 × 108 ms−1, the difference in optical distance between the two subpulses increases by 300 μmand the pulse delay will be consequently increased by 1 ps. Herein, we use the temporally-shaped femtosecond laser pulse delay (
τ 2
) of 10 ps.
